X:4587419
%%MIDI ratio 2 1
%%pagescale .80
T:Valse Louise
T:Valse Aldor or Valse Armandine
C:Aldor Morin or Fortunat Malouin (maybe)
S:Philippe Bruneau, $2Au Symposium de LÃ©vis$0 (1989). Archives du MusÃ©e canadien des
S:civilisations, Archives TDCA-2003PB, 2003.
S:Jean Duval, $2La Musique de Fortunat Malouin (1870-1935); 10 piÃ¨ces avec commentaires
S:et une biographie.$0, 2020.
H:In $2The Waltz Book II$0, Bill Matthiesen says, quoting Lisa Ornstein, that Philippe Bruneau
H:and Aldor Morin both sometimes played for the Soucy Family's $2Chez Isidore$0 television
H:show. "Philippe Bruneau popularized this waltz under the name $2Valse Aldor$0. although
H:its original and correct title is $2Valse Louise$0." On this recording he calls it 
H:$2Valse Armandine$0. Jean Duval wrote that Fortunat Malouin might have composed the waltz,
H:naming it for his daughter Armandine who accompanied him on his records. He recorded it 
H:in 1929, at which time Aldor Morin was 8 years old. But Aldor Morin had already been 
H:playing for a couple years, having studied with Madame Bolduc, so he can't be ruled
H:out as the composer.
H:
H:This is as accurate a transcription of Philippe Bruneau's version of the tune as I'm
H:capable of doing. If you're familiar with his playing you're likely to be aware that
H:his ornamentation is complex, and he plays many variations, On this recording there
H:are a number of other instruments that create a rich sound that's great to listen to
H:but hard to transcribe.
H:
H:I include some of his idiosyncratic phrasing and timing. He doesn't play each detail
H:all the time; and he has other variations not represented here. In the descending run
H:of triplets he sometimes only plays some notes as triplets. If you want to avoid the high
H:D at the end of the A part, the last 4 measures could be played an octave lower.
N:From NH Country Dance (URL below), along with many New England, Canadian & Swedish
N:tunes, and resources for abc notation and New England traditional music and dance.
